<!--DOCTYPE section SYSTEM "file:/opt/share/xml/Oxygen/docbook/dtd/docbookx.dtd"--><ns5546:section xmlns:ns5546="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.shell.scripting.introduction.whatIsShellScript">

  <ns5547:title xmlns:ns5547="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">What is a shell script</ns5547:title>
  <ns5548:para xmlns:ns5548="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    A shell is a command interface to the operating system kernel 
    (see <ns5549:xref xmlns:ns5549="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" linkend="resources.information.platforms.linux.shell.shells"/>).
    A shell script is a text file which contains a sequence of 
    such commands, though shell scripts do support
    conditional paths and loops.
    <ns5550:note xmlns:ns5550="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns5551:para xmlns:ns5551="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Linux shell scripts are similar but typically more powerful than  batch files on Windows
        or MSDos.
      </ns5551:para>
    </ns5550:note>
  </ns5548:para>
</ns5546:section>